# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: integrity-measurement
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Hashing is a one-directional mathematical operation which is quick to calculate, yet hard to reverse.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] So password storage and digital signatures benefit from hashes.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Even a small change in the input results in a very different hash.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] So it is useful to check if two copies of data or software match.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Typically the operation works on a block of input data; the hash output is then hashed with the next block, creating a new hash reflecting everything to that point; again and again until the final hash reflects everything through the final block.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Cryptographic hash functions have many information-security applications, notably in digital signatures, message authentication codes (MACs), and other forms of authentication.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] They can also be used as ordinary hash functions, to index data in hash tables, for fingerprinting, to detect duplicate data or uniquely identify files, and as checksums to detect accidental data corruption.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Indeed, in information-security contexts, cryptographic hash values are sometimes called (*digital*) *fingerprints*, *checksums*, (*message*) *digests*, or just *hash values*, even though all these terms stand for more general functions with rather different properties and purposes.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Non-cryptographic hash functions are used in hash tables and to detect accidental errors; their constructions frequently provide no resistance to a deliberate attack.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, a denial-of-service attack on hash tables is possible if the collisions are easy to find, as in the case of linear cyclic redundancy check (CRC) functions.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Most cryptographic hash functions are designed to take a string of any length as input and produce a fixed-length hash value.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] A cryptographic hash function must be able to withstand all known types of cryptanalytic attack.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Collision resistance implies second pre-image resistance but does not imply pre-image resistance.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] The weaker assumption is always preferred in theoretical cryptography, but in practice, a hash-function that is only second pre-image resistant is considered insecure and is therefore not recommended for real applications.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Informally, these properties mean that a malicious adversary cannot replace or modify the input data without changing its digest.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Thus, if two strings have the same digest, one can be very confident that they are identical.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Second pre-image resistance prevents an attacker from crafting a document with the same hash as a document the attacker cannot control.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Collision resistance prevents an attacker from creating two distinct documents with the same hash.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] A function meeting these criteria may still have undesirable properties.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Currently, popular cryptographic hash functions are vulnerable to *length-extension* attacks: given hash(*m*) and len(*m*) but not *m*, by choosing a suitable *m*′ an attacker can calculate hash(*m* ∥ *m*′), where ∥ denotes concatenation.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] This property can be used to break naive authentication schemes based on hash functions.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] The HMAC construction works around these problems.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] In practice, collision resistance is insufficient for many practical uses.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] In addition to collision resistance, it should be impossible for an adversary to find two messages with substantially similar digests; or to infer any useful information about the data, given only its digest.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] In particular, a hash function should behave as much as possible like a random function (often called a random oracle in proofs of security) while still being deterministic and efficiently computable.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] This rules out functions like the SWIFFT function, which can be rigorously proven to be collision-resistant assuming that certain problems on ideal lattices are computationally difficult, but, as a linear function, does not satisfy these additional properties.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Checksum algorithms, such as CRC-32 and other cyclic redundancy checks, are designed to meet much weaker requirements and are generally unsuitable as cryptographic hash functions.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, a CRC was used for message integrity in the WEP encryption standard, but an attack was readily discovered, which exploited the linearity of the checksum.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] In cryptographic practice, "difficult" generally means "almost certainly beyond the reach of any adversary who must be prevented from breaking the system for as long as the security of the system is deemed important".
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] The meaning of the term is therefore somewhat dependent on the application since the effort that a malicious agent may put into the task is usually proportional to their expected gain.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] However, since the needed effort usually multiplies with the digest length, even a thousand-fold advantage in processing power can be neutralized by adding a dozen bits to the latter.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] For messages selected from a limited set of messages, for example passwords or other short messages, it can be feasible to invert a hash by trying all possible messages in the set.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Because cryptographic hash functions are typically designed to be computed quickly, special key derivation functions that require greater computing resources have been developed that make such brute-force attacks more difficult.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] In some theoretical analyses "difficult" has a specific mathematical meaning, such as "not solvable in asymptotic polynomial time".
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Such interpretations of *difficulty* are important in the study of provably secure cryptographic hash functions but do not usually have a strong connection to practical security.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, an exponential-time algorithm can sometimes still be fast enough to make a feasible attack.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Conversely, a polynomial-time algorithm (e.g., one that requires *n*20 steps for *n*-digit keys) may be too slow for any practical use.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] An illustration of the potential use of a cryptographic hash is as follows: Alice poses a tough math problem to Bob and claims that she has solved it.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Bob would like to try it himself, but would yet like to be sure that Alice is not bluffing.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Therefore, Alice writes down her solution, computes its hash, and tells Bob the hash value (whilst keeping the solution secret).
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Then, when Bob comes up with the solution himself a few days later, Alice can prove that she had the solution earlier by revealing it and having Bob hash it and then check that it matches the hash value given to him before.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] An important application of secure hashes is the verification of message integrity.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Comparing message digests (hash digests over the message) calculated before, and after, transmission can determine whether any changes have been made to the message or file.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5, SHA-1, or SHA-2 hash digests are sometimes published on websites or forums to allow verification of integrity for downloaded files, including files retrieved using file sharing such as mirroring.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] This practice establishes a chain of trust as long as the hashes are posted on a trusted site – usually the originating site – authenticated by HTTPS.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Using a cryptographic hash and a chain of trust detects malicious changes to the file.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Non-cryptographic error-detecting codes such as cyclic redundancy checks only prevent against *non-malicious* alterations of the file, since an intentional spoof can readily be crafted to have the colliding code value.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Almost all digital signature schemes require a cryptographic hash to be calculated over the message.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] This allows the signature calculation to be performed on the relatively small, statically sized hash digest.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] The message is considered authentic if the signature verification succeeds given the signature and recalculated hash digest over the message.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] So the message integrity property of the cryptographic hash is used to create secure and efficient digital signature schemes.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Password verification commonly relies on cryptographic hashes.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Storing all user passwords as cleartext can result in a massive security breach if the password file is compromised.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] One way to reduce this danger is to only store the hash digest of each password.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] To authenticate a user, the password presented by the user is hashed and compared with the stored hash.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] A password reset method is required when password hashing is performed; original passwords cannot be recalculated from the stored hash value.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] However, use of standard cryptographic hash functions, such as the SHA series, is no longer considered safe for password storage.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] These algorithms are designed to be computed quickly, so if the hashed values are compromised, it is possible to try guessed passwords at high rates.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Common graphics processing units can try billions of possible passwords each second.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Password hash functions that perform key stretching – such as PBKDF2, scrypt or Argon2 – commonly use repeated invocations of a cryptographic hash to increase the time (and in some cases computer memory) required to perform brute-force attacks on stored password hash digests.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] For details, see § Attacks on hashed passwords.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] A password hash also requires the use of a large random, non-secret salt value that can be stored with the password hash.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] The salt is hashed with the password, altering the password hash mapping for each password, thereby making it infeasible for an adversary to store tables of precomputed hash values to which the password hash digest can be compared or to test a large number of purloined hash values in parallel.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] A proof-of-work system (or protocol, or function) is an economic measure to deter denial-of-service attacks and other service abuses such as spam on a network by requiring some work from the service requester, usually meaning processing time by a computer.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] A key feature of these schemes is their asymmetry: the work must be moderately hard (but feasible) on the requester side but easy to check for the service provider.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] One popular system – used in Bitcoin mining and Hashcash – uses partial hash inversions to prove that work was done, to unlock a mining reward in Bitcoin, and as a good-will token to send an e-mail in Hashcash.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] The sender is required to find a message whose hash value begins with a number of zero bits.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] The average work that the sender needs to perform in order to find a valid message is exponential in the number of zero bits required in the hash value, while the recipient can verify the validity of the message by executing a single hash function.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] For instance, in Hashcash, a sender is asked to generate a header whose 160-bit SHA-1 hash value has the first 20 bits as zeros.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] The sender will, on average, have to try 219 times to find a valid header.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] A message digest can also serve as a means of reliably identifying a file; several source code management systems, including Git, Mercurial and Monotone, use the sha1sum of various types of content (file content, directory trees, ancestry information, etc.) to uniquely identify them.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Hashes are used to identify files on peer-to-peer filesharing networks.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, in an ed2k link, an MD4-variant hash is combined with the file size, providing sufficient information for locating file sources, downloading the file, and verifying its contents.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Such file hashes are often the top hash of a hash list or a hash tree, which allows for additional benefits.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] One of the main applications of a hash function is to allow the fast look-up of data in a hash table.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Being hash functions of a particular kind, cryptographic hash functions lend themselves well to this application too.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] However, compared with standard hash functions, cryptographic hash functions tend to be much more expensive computationally.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Content-addressable storage (CAS), also referred to as content-addressed storage or fixed-content storage, is a way to store information so it can be retrieved based on its content, not its name or location.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] It has been used for high-speed storage and retrieval of fixed content, such as documents stored for compliance with government regulations.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Content-addressable storage is similar to content-addressable memory.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] CAS systems work by passing the content of the file through a cryptographic hash function to generate a unique key, the "content address".
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] The file system's directory stores these addresses and a pointer to the physical storage of the content.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Because an attempt to store the same file will generate the same key, CAS systems ensure that the files within them are unique, and because changing the file will result in a new key, CAS systems provide assurance that the file is unchanged.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] CAS became a significant market during the 2000s, especially after the introduction of the 2002 Sarbanes–Oxley Act in the United States which required the storage of enormous numbers of documents for long periods and retrieved only rarely.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Ever-increasing performance of traditional file systems and new software systems have eroded the value of legacy CAS systems, which have become increasingly rare after roughly 2018.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] However, the principles of content addressability continue to be of great interest to computer scientists, and form the core of numerous emerging technologies, such as peer-to-peer file sharing, cryptocurrencies, and distributed computing.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] There are several methods to use a block cipher to build a cryptographic hash function, specifically a one-way compression function.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] The methods resemble the block cipher modes of operation usually used for encryption.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Many well-known hash functions, including MD4, MD5, SHA-1 and SHA-2, are built from block-cipher-like components designed for the purpose, with feedback to ensure that the resulting function is not invertible.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 finalists included functions with block-cipher-like components (e.g., Skein, BLAKE) though the function finally selected, Keccak, was built on a cryptographic sponge instead.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] A standard block cipher such as AES can be used in place of these custom block ciphers; that might be useful when an embedded system needs to implement both encryption and hashing with minimal code size or hardware area.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] However, that approach can have costs in efficiency and security.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] The ciphers in hash functions are built for hashing: they use large keys and blocks, can efficiently change keys every block, and have been designed and vetted for resistance to related-key attacks.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] General-purpose ciphers tend to have different design goals.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] In particular, AES has key and block sizes that make it nontrivial to use to generate long hash values; AES encryption becomes less efficient when the key changes each block; and related-key attacks make it potentially less secure for use in a hash function than for encryption.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] A hash function must be able to process an arbitrary-length message into a fixed-length output.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] This can be achieved by breaking the input up into a series of equally sized blocks, and operating on them in sequence using a one-way compression function.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] The compression function can either be specially designed for hashing or be built from a block cipher.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] A hash function built with the Merkle–Damgård construction is as resistant to collisions as is its compression function; any collision for the full hash function can be traced back to a collision in the compression function.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] The last block processed should also be unambiguously length padded; this is crucial to the security of this construction.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] This construction is called the Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Most common classical hash functions, including SHA-1 and MD5, take this form.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] A straightforward application of the Merkle–Damgård construction, where the size of hash output is equal to the internal state size (between each compression step), results in a **narrow-pipe** hash design.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] This design causes many inherent flaws, including length-extension, multicollisions, long message attacks, generate-and-paste attacks, and also cannot be parallelized.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] As a result, modern hash functions are built on **wide-pipe** constructions that have a larger internal state size – which range from tweaks of the Merkle–Damgård construction to new constructions such as the sponge construction and HAIFA construction.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] None of the entrants in the NIST hash function competition use a classical Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Meanwhile, truncating the output of a longer hash, such as used in SHA-512/256, also defeats many of these attacks.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Hash functions can be used to build other cryptographic primitives.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] For these other primitives to be cryptographically secure, care must be taken to build them correctly.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Message authentication codes (MACs) (also called keyed hash functions) are often built from hash functions.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Just as block ciphers can be used to build hash functions, hash functions can be used to build block ciphers.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Luby-Rackoff constructions using hash functions can be provably secure if the underlying hash function is secure.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Also, many hash functions (including SHA-1 and SHA-2) are built by using a special-purpose block cipher in a Davies–Meyer or other construction.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] That cipher can also be used in a conventional mode of operation, without the same security guarantees; for example, SHACAL, BEAR and LION.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Pseudorandom number generators (PRNGs) can be built using hash functions.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] This is done by combining a (secret) random seed with a counter and hashing it.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Some hash functions, such as Skein, Keccak, and RadioGatún, output an arbitrarily long stream and can be used as a stream cipher, and stream ciphers can also be built from fixed-length digest hash functions.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Often this is done by first building a cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator and then using its stream of random bytes as keystream.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] SEAL is a stream cipher that uses SHA-1 to generate internal tables, which are then used in a keystream generator more or less unrelated to the hash algorithm.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] SEAL is not guaranteed to be as strong (or weak) as SHA-1.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Similarly, the key expansion of the HC-128 and HC-256 stream ciphers makes heavy use of the SHA-256 hash function.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Concatenating outputs from multiple hash functions provide collision resistance as good as the strongest of the algorithms included in the concatenated result.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, older versions of Transport Layer Security (TLS) and Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) used concatenated MD5 and SHA-1 sums.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] This ensures that a method to find collisions in one of the hash functions does not defeat data protected by both hash functions.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] For Merkle–Damgård construction hash functions, the concatenated function is as collision-resistant as its strongest component, but not more collision-resistant.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Antoine Joux observed that 2-collisions lead to *n*-collisions: if it is feasible for an attacker to find two messages with the same MD5 hash, then they can find as many additional messages with that same MD5 hash as they desire, with no greater difficulty.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Among those *n* messages with the same MD5 hash, there is likely to be a collision in SHA-1.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] The additional work needed to find the SHA-1 collision (beyond the exponential birthday search) requires only polynomial time.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] There are many cryptographic hash algorithms; this section lists a few algorithms that are referenced relatively often.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] A more extensive list can be found on the page containing a comparison of cryptographic hash functions.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5 was designed by Ronald Rivest in 1991 to replace an earlier hash function, MD4, and was specified in 1992 as RFC 1321.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Collisions against MD5 can be calculated within seconds, which makes the algorithm unsuitable for most use cases where a cryptographic hash is required.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5 produces a digest of 128 bits (16 bytes).
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] The original specification – now commonly called SHA-0 – of the algorithm was published in 1993 under the title Secure Hash Standard, FIPS PUB 180, by U.S. government standards agency NIST (National Institute of Standards and Technology).
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] It was withdrawn by the NSA shortly after publication and was superseded by the revised version, published in 1995 in FIPS PUB 180-1 and commonly designated SHA-1.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Collisions against the full SHA-1 algorithm can be produced using the shattered attack and the hash function should be considered broken.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-1 produces a hash digest of 160 bits (20 bytes).
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Documents may refer to SHA-1 as just "SHA", even though this may conflict with the other Secure Hash Algorithms such as SHA-0, SHA-2, and SHA-3.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD (RACE Integrity Primitives Evaluation Message Digest) is a family of cryptographic hash functions developed in Leuven, Belgium, by Hans Dobbertin, Antoon Bosselaers, and Bart Preneel at the COSIC research group at the Katholieke Universiteit Leuven, and first published in 1996.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD was based upon the design principles used in MD4 and is similar in performance to the more popular SHA-1.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD-160 has, however, not been broken.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] As the name implies, RIPEMD-160 produces a hash digest of 160 bits (20 bytes).
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool is a cryptographic hash function designed by Vincent Rijmen and Paulo S.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Barreto, who first described it in 2000.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool is based on a substantially modified version of the Advanced Encryption Standard (AES).
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool produces a hash digest of 512 bits (64 bytes).
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-2 (Secure Hash Algorithm 2) is a set of cryptographic hash functions designed by the United States National Security Agency (NSA), first published in 2001.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] They are built using the Merkle–Damgård structure, from a one-way compression function itself built using the Davies–Meyer structure from a (classified) specialized block cipher.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-2 basically consists of two hash algorithms: SHA-256 and SHA-512.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-224 is a variant of SHA-256 with different starting values and truncated output.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-512 is more secure than SHA-256 and is commonly faster than SHA-256 on 64-bit machines such as AMD64.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] The output size in bits is given by the extension to the "SHA" name, so SHA-224 has an output size of 224 bits (28 bytes); SHA-256, 32 bytes; SHA-384, 48 bytes; and SHA-512, 64 bytes.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 (Secure Hash Algorithm 3) was released by NIST on August 5, 2015.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 is a subset of the broader cryptographic primitive family Keccak.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] The Keccak algorithm is the work of Guido Bertoni, Joan Daemen, Michael Peeters, and Gilles Van Assche.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Keccak is based on a sponge construction, which can also be used to build other cryptographic primitives such as a stream cipher.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 provides the same output sizes as SHA-2: 224, 256, 384, and 512 bits.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Configurable output sizes can also be obtained using the SHAKE-128 and SHAKE-256 functions.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Here the -128 and -256 extensions to the name imply the security strength of the function rather than the output size in bits.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE2, an improved version of BLAKE, was announced on December 21, 2012.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] It was created by Jean-Philippe Aumasson, Samuel Neves, Zooko Wilcox-O'Hearn, and Christian Winnerlein with the goal of replacing the widely used but broken MD5 and SHA-1 algorithms.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] When run on 64-bit x64 and ARM architectures, BLAKE2b is faster than SHA-3, SHA-2, SHA-1, and MD5.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Although BLAKE and BLAKE2 have not been standardized as SHA-3 has, BLAKE2 has been used in many protocols including the Argon2 password hash, for the high efficiency that it offers on modern CPUs.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] As BLAKE was a candidate for SHA-3, BLAKE and BLAKE2 both offer the same output sizes as SHA-3 – including a configurable output size.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE3, an improved version of BLAKE2, was announced on January 9, 2020.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] It was created by Jack O'Connor, Jean-Philippe Aumasson, Samuel Neves, and Zooko Wilcox-O'Hearn.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE3 is a single algorithm, in contrast to BLAKE and BLAKE2, which are algorithm families with multiple variants.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] The BLAKE3 compression function is closely based on that of BLAKE2s, with the biggest difference being that the number of rounds is reduced from 10 to 7.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Internally, BLAKE3 is a Merkle tree, and it supports higher degrees of parallelism than BLAKE2.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] There is a long list of cryptographic hash functions but many have been found to be vulnerable and should not be used.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Even if a hash function has never been broken, a successful attack against a weakened variant may undermine the experts' confidence.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] For instance, in August 2004 collisions were found in several then-popular hash functions, including MD5.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] These weaknesses called into question the security of stronger algorithms derived from the weak hash functions – in particular, SHA-1 (a strengthened version of SHA-0), RIPEMD-128, and RIPEMD-160 (both strengthened versions of RIPEMD).
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] On August 12, 2004, Joux, Carribault, Lemuel, and Jalby announced a collision for the full SHA-0 algorithm.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Joux et al. accomplished this using a generalization of the Chabaud and Joux attack.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] They found that the collision had complexity 251 and took about 80,000 CPU hours on a supercomputer with 256 Itanium 2 processors – equivalent to 13 days of full-time use of the supercomputer.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] In February 2005, an attack on SHA-1 was reported that would find collision in about 269 hashing operations, rather than the 280 expected for a 160-bit hash function.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] In August 2005, another attack on SHA-1 was reported that would find collisions in 263 operations.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Other theoretical weaknesses of SHA-1 have been known, and in February 2017 Google announced a collision in SHA-1.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Security researchers recommend that new applications can avoid these problems by using later members of the SHA family, such as SHA-2, or using techniques such as randomized hashing that do not require collision resistance.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] A successful, practical attack broke MD5 (used within certificates for Transport Layer Security) in 2008.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Many cryptographic hashes are based on the Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] All cryptographic hashes that directly use the full output of a Merkle–Damgård construction are vulnerable to length extension attacks.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] This makes the MD5, SHA-1, RIPEMD-160, Whirlpool, and the SHA-256 / SHA-512 hash algorithms all vulnerable to this specific attack.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3, BLAKE2, BLAKE3, and the truncated SHA-2 variants are not vulnerable to this type of attack.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Rather than store plain user passwords, controlled-access systems frequently store the hash of each user's password in a file or database.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] When someone requests access, the password they submit is hashed and compared with the stored value.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] If the database is stolen (an all-too-frequent occurrence), the thief will only have the hash values, not the passwords.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Passwords may still be retrieved by an attacker from the hashes, because most people choose passwords in predictable ways.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Lists of common passwords are widely circulated and many passwords are short enough that even all possible combinations may be tested if calculation of the hash does not take too much time.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] The use of cryptographic salt prevents some attacks, such as building files of precomputing hash values, e.g. rainbow tables.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] But searches on the order of 100 billion tests per second are possible with high-end graphics processors, making direct attacks possible even with salt.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] The United States National Institute of Standards and Technology recommends storing passwords using special hashes called key derivation functions (KDFs) that have been created to slow brute force searches.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] Slow hashes include pbkdf2, bcrypt, scrypt, argon2, Balloon and some recent modes of Unix crypt.
[src:integrity-measurement/cryptographic-hash-function] For KDFs that perform multiple hashes to slow execution, NIST recommends an iteration count of 10,000 or more.
[src:integrity-measurement/file-integrity-monitoring] Generally, the act of performing file integrity monitoring is automated using internal controls such as an application or process.
[src:integrity-measurement/file-integrity-monitoring] Such monitoring can be performed randomly, at a defined polling interval, or in real-time.
[src:integrity-measurement/file-integrity-monitoring] Changes to configurations, files and file attributes across the IT infrastructure are common, but hidden within a large volume of daily changes can be the few that impact file or configuration integrity.
[src:integrity-measurement/file-integrity-monitoring] These changes can also reduce security posture and in some cases may be leading indicators of a breach in progress.
[src:integrity-measurement/file-integrity-monitoring] Multiple compliance objectives indicate file integrity monitoring as a requirement.
[src:integrity-measurement/file-verification] File integrity can be compromised, usually referred to as the file becoming corrupted.
[src:integrity-measurement/file-verification] A file can become corrupted by a variety of ways: faulty storage media, errors in transmission, write errors during copying or moving, software bugs, and so on.
[src:integrity-measurement/file-verification] Hash-based verification ensures that a file has not been corrupted by comparing the file's hash value to a previously calculated value.
[src:integrity-measurement/file-verification] If these values match, the file is presumed to be unmodified.
[src:integrity-measurement/file-verification] Due to the nature of hash functions, hash collisions may result in false positives, but the likelihood of collisions is often negligible with random corruption.
[src:integrity-measurement/file-verification] It is often desirable to verify that a file hasn't been modified in transmission or storage by untrusted parties, for example, to include malicious code such as viruses or backdoors.
[src:integrity-measurement/file-verification] To verify the authenticity, a classical hash function is not enough as they are not designed to be collision resistant; it is computationally trivial for an attacker to cause deliberate hash collisions, meaning that a malicious change in the file is not detected by a hash comparison.
[src:integrity-measurement/file-verification] In cryptography, this attack is called a preimage attack.
[src:integrity-measurement/file-verification] For this purpose, cryptographic hash functions are employed often.
[src:integrity-measurement/file-verification] As long as the hash sums cannot be tampered with — for example, if they are communicated over a secure channel — the files can be presumed to be intact.
[src:integrity-measurement/file-verification] Alternatively, digital signatures can be employed to assure tamper resistance.
[src:integrity-measurement/file-verification] A **checksum file** is a small file that contains the checksums of other files.
[src:integrity-measurement/file-verification] There are a few well-known checksum file formats.
[src:integrity-measurement/file-verification] Several utilities, such as md5deep, can use such checksum files to automatically verify an entire directory of files in one operation.
[src:integrity-measurement/file-verification] The particular hash algorithm used is often indicated by the file extension of the checksum file.
[src:integrity-measurement/file-verification] The ".sha1" file extension indicates a checksum file containing 160-bit SHA-1 hashes in sha1sum format.
[src:integrity-measurement/file-verification] The ".md5" file extension, or a file named "MD5SUMS", indicates a checksum file containing 128-bit MD5 hashes in md5sum format.
[src:integrity-measurement/file-verification] The ".sfv" file extension indicates a checksum file containing 32-bit CRC32 checksums in simple file verification format.
[src:integrity-measurement/file-verification] The "crc.list" file indicates a checksum file containing 32-bit CRC checksums in brik format.
[src:integrity-measurement/file-verification] As of 2012, best practice recommendations is to use SHA-2 or SHA-3 to generate new file integrity digests; and to accept MD5 and SHA-1 digests for backward compatibility if stronger digests are not available.
[src:integrity-measurement/file-verification] The theoretically weaker SHA-1, the weaker MD5, or much weaker CRC were previously commonly used for file integrity checks.
[src:integrity-measurement/linux-security-modules] LSM was designed in order to answer all the requirements for successfully implementing a mandatory access control module, while imposing the fewest possible changes to the Linux kernel.
[src:integrity-measurement/linux-security-modules] LSM avoids the approach of system call interposition used by Systrace because it doesn't scale to multiprocessor kernels and is subject to TOCTTOU (race) attacks.
[src:integrity-measurement/linux-security-modules] Instead, LSM inserts "hooks" (upcalls to the module) at every point in the kernel where a user-level system-call is about to result with an access to an important internal kernel-object like inodes and process control blocks.
[src:integrity-measurement/linux-security-modules] LSM is narrowly scoped to solve the problem of access control, while not imposing a large and complex change-patch on the mainstream kernel.
[src:integrity-measurement/linux-security-modules] It isn't intended to be a general "*hook*" or "*upcall*" mechanism, nor does it support operating system-level virtualization.
[src:integrity-measurement/linux-security-modules] LSM's access-control goal is very closely related to the problem of system auditing, but is subtly different.
[src:integrity-measurement/linux-security-modules] Auditing requires that every attempt at access be recorded.
[src:integrity-measurement/linux-security-modules] LSM cannot deliver this, because it would require a great many more hooks, in order to detect cases where the kernel "*short circuits*" failing system-calls and returns an error code before getting near significant objects.
[src:integrity-measurement/linux-security-modules] The LSM design is described in the paper "Linux Security Modules: General Security Support for the Linux Kernel" presented at USENIX Security Symposium 2002.
[src:integrity-measurement/linux-security-modules] At the same conference was the paper "Using CQUAL for Static Analysis of Authorization Hook Placement" which studied automatic static analysis of the kernel code to verify that all of the necessary hooks have actually been inserted into the Linux kernel.
[src:integrity-measurement/linux-security-modules] At the 2001 Linux Kernel Summit, the NSA proposed that SELinux be included in Linux 2.5.
[src:integrity-measurement/linux-security-modules] Linus Torvalds rejected SELinux at that time, because he observed that there are many different security projects in development, and since they all differ, the security community has not yet formed consensus on the ultimate security model.
[src:integrity-measurement/linux-security-modules] Instead, Linus charged the security community to "make it a module".
[src:integrity-measurement/linux-security-modules] In response, Crispin Cowan proposed LSM: an interface for the Linux kernel that provides sufficient "hooks" (upcalls) from within the Linux kernel to a loadable module so as to allow the module to enforce mandatory access controls.
[src:integrity-measurement/linux-security-modules] Development of LSM over the next two years was conducted by the LSM community, including substantial contributions from the Immunix Corporation, the NSA, McAfee, IBM, Silicon Graphics, and many independent contributors.
[src:integrity-measurement/linux-security-modules] LSM was ultimately accepted into the Linux kernel mainstream and was included as a standard part of Linux 2.6 in December 2003.
[src:integrity-measurement/linux-security-modules] In 2006, some kernel developers observed that SELinux was the only widely used LSM module included in the mainstream Linux kernel source tree.
[src:integrity-measurement/linux-security-modules] If there is to be only one widely used LSM module, it was reasoned, then the indirection of LSM is unnecessary, and LSM should be removed and replaced with SELinux itself.
[src:integrity-measurement/linux-security-modules] LSM is likely to remain since additional security modules Smack (version 2.6.25), TOMOYO Linux (version 2.6.30, June 2009) and AppArmor (version 2.6.36) were accepted in the mainline kernel.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] A hash tree allows efficient and secure verification of the contents of a large data structure.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] A hash tree is a generalization of a hash list and a hash chain.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] Demonstrating that a leaf node is a part of a given binary hash tree requires computing a number of hashes proportional to the logarithm of the number of leaf nodes in the tree.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] Conversely, in a hash list, the number is proportional to the number of leaf nodes itself.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] A Merkle tree is therefore an efficient example of a cryptographic commitment scheme, in which the root of the tree is seen as a commitment and leaf nodes may be revealed and proven to be part of the original commitment.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] The concept of a hash tree is named after Ralph Merkle, who patented it in 1979.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] Hash trees can be used to verify any kind of data stored, handled and transferred in and between computers.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] They can help ensure that data blocks received from other peers in a peer-to-peer network are received undamaged and unaltered, and even to check that the other peers do not lie and send fake blocks.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] Suggestions have been made to use hash trees in trusted computing systems.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] A hash tree is a tree of hashes in which the leaves (i.e., leaf nodes, sometimes also called "leafs") are hashes of data blocks in, for instance, a file or set of files.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] Nodes farther up in the tree are the hashes of their respective children.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] For example, in the above picture *hash 0* is the result of hashing the concatenation of *hash 0-0* and *hash 0-1*.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] That is, *hash 0* = *hash*( *hash 0-0* + *hash 0-1* ) where "+" denotes concatenation.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] Most hash tree implementations are binary (two child nodes under each node) but they can just as well use many more child nodes under each node.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] Usually, a cryptographic hash function such as SHA-2 is used for the hashing.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] If the hash tree only needs to protect against unintentional damage, non-cryptographic checksums such as CRCs can be used.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] In the top of a hash tree there is a *top hash* (or *root hash* or *master hash*).
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] Before downloading a file on a P2P network, in most cases the top hash is acquired from a trusted source, for instance a friend or a web site that is known to have good recommendations of files to download.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] When the top hash is available, the hash tree can be received from any non-trusted source, like any peer in the P2P network.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] Then, the received hash tree is checked against the trusted top hash, and if the hash tree is damaged or fake, another hash tree from another source will be tried until the program finds one that matches the top hash.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] The main difference from a hash list is that one branch of the hash tree can be downloaded at a time and the integrity of each branch can be checked immediately, even though the whole tree is not available yet.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] For example, in the picture, the integrity of *data block L2* can be verified immediately if the tree already contains *hash 0-0* and *hash 1* by hashing the data block and iteratively combining the result with *hash 0-0* and then *hash 1* and finally comparing the result with the *top hash*.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] Similarly, the integrity of *data block L3* can be verified if the tree already has *hash 1-1* and *hash 0*.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] This can be an advantage since it is efficient to split files up in very small data blocks so that only small blocks have to be re-downloaded if they get damaged.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] If the hashed file is big, such a hash list or hash chain becomes fairly big.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] But if it is a tree, one small branch can be downloaded quickly, the integrity of the branch can be checked, and then the downloading of data blocks can start.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] The Merkle hash root does not indicate the tree depth, enabling a second-preimage attack in which an attacker creates a document other than the original that has the same Merkle hash root.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] For the example above, an attacker can create a new document containing two data blocks, where the first is *hash 0-0* + *hash 0-1*, and the second is *hash 1-0* + *hash 1-1*.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] One simple fix is defined in Certificate Transparency: when computing leaf node hashes, a 0x00 byte is prepended to the hash data, while 0x01 is prepended when computing internal node hashes.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] Limiting the hash tree size is a prerequisite of some formal security proofs, and helps in making some proofs tighter.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] Some implementations limit the tree depth using hash tree depth prefixes before hashes, so any extracted hash chain is defined to be valid only if the prefix decreases at each step and is still positive when the leaf is reached.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] The Tiger tree hash is a widely used form of hash tree.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] It uses a binary hash tree (two child nodes under each node), usually has a data block size of 1024 bytes and uses the Tiger hash.
[src:integrity-measurement/merkle-tree] Tiger tree hashes are used in Gnutella, Gnutella2, and Direct Connect P2P file sharing protocols and in file sharing applications such as Phex, BearShare, LimeWire, Shareaza, DC++ and gtk-gnutella.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] A **Trusted Platform Module** (**TPM**) is a secure cryptoprocessor that implements the **ISO/IEC 11889** standard.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] Common uses are verifying that the boot process starts from a trusted combination of hardware and software and storing disk encryption keys.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] A TPM 2.0 implementation is part of the Windows 11 system requirements.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] The first TPM version that was deployed was 1.1b in 2003.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] Trusted Platform Module (TPM) was conceived by a computer industry consortium called Trusted Computing Group (TCG).
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] It evolved into *TPM Main Specification Version 1.2* which was standardized by International Organization for Standardization (ISO) and International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) in 2009 as ISO/IEC 11889:2009.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] *TPM Main Specification Version 1.2* was finalized on 3 March 2011 completing its revision.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] On April 9, 2014, the Trusted Computing Group announced a major upgrade to their specification entitled *TPM Library Specification 2.0*.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] The group continues work on the standard incorporating errata, algorithmic additions and new commands, with its most recent edition published as 2.0 in November 2019.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] When a new revision is released, it is divided into multiple parts by the Trusted Computing Group.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] Each part consists of a document that makes up the whole of the new TPM specification.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] While TPM 2.0 addresses many of the same use cases and has similar features, the details are different.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] TPM 2.0 is not backward compatible with TPM 1.2.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] The TPM 2.0 policy authorization includes the 1.2 HMAC, locality, physical presence, and PCR.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] It adds authorization based on an asymmetric digital signature, indirection to another authorization secret, counters and time limits, NVRAM values, a particular command or command parameters, and physical presence.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] It permits the ANDing and ORing of these authorization primitives to construct complex authorization policies.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] Computer programs can use a TPM for the authentication of hardware devices, since each TPM chip has a unique and secret Endorsement Key (EK) burned in as it is produced.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] Security embedded in hardware provides more protection than a software-only solution.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] Its use is restricted in some countries.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] The primary scope of TPM is to ensure the integrity of a platform during boot time.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] In this context, "integrity" means "behaves as intended", and a "platform" is any computer device regardless of its operating system.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] This is to ensure that the boot process starts from a trusted combination of hardware and software, and continues until the operating system has fully booted and applications are running.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] When TPM is used, the firmware and the operating system are responsible for ensuring integrity.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] For example, the Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) can use TPM to form a root of trust: The TPM contains several Platform Configuration Registers (PCRs) that allow secure storage and reporting of security-relevant metrics.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] These metrics can be used to detect changes to previous configurations and decide how to proceed.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] Examples of such use can be found in Linux Unified Key Setup (LUKS), BitLocker and PrivateCore vCage memory encryption.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] Another example of platform integrity via TPM is in the use of Microsoft Office 365 licensing and Outlook Exchange.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] Another example of TPM use for platform integrity is the Trusted Execution Technology (TXT), which creates a chain of trust.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] It could remotely attest that a computer is using the specified hardware and software.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] Full disk encryption utilities, such as dm-crypt, can use this technology to protect the keys used to encrypt the computer's storage devices and provide integrity authentication for a trusted boot pathway that includes firmware and the boot sector.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] In 2006, new laptops began being sold with a built-in TPM chip.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] In the future, this concept could be co-located on an existing motherboard chip in computers, or any other device where the TPM facilities could be employed, such as a cellphone.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] On a PC, either the Low Pin Count (LPC) bus or the Serial Peripheral Interface (SPI) bus is used to connect to the TPM chip.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] The official TCG reference implementation of the TPM 2.0 Specification has been developed by Microsoft.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] It is licensed under BSD License and the source code is available on GitHub.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] In 2018, Intel open-sourced its Trusted Platform Module 2.0 (TPM2) software stack with support for Linux and Microsoft Windows.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] The source code is hosted on GitHub and licensed under BSD License.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] Infineon funded the development of an open source TPM middleware that complies with the Software Stack (TSS) Enhanced System API (ESAPI) specification of the TCG.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] It was developed by Fraunhofer Institute for Secure Information Technology (SIT).
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] IBM's Software TPM 2.0 is an implementation of the TCG TPM 2.0 specification.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] It is based on the TPM specification Parts 3 and 4 and source code donated by Microsoft.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] It contains additional files to complete the implementation.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] The source code is hosted on SourceForge and GitHub and licensed under BSD License.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] In 2022, AMD announced that under certain circumstances their fTPM implementation causes performance problems.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] A fix is available in form of a BIOS-Update.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] The Trusted Computing Group (TCG) has faced resistance to the deployment of this technology in some areas, where some authors see possible uses not specifically related to Trusted Computing, which may raise privacy concerns.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] The concerns include the abuse of remote validation of software to decide what software is allowed to run, and possible ways to follow actions taken by the user and record them in a database in a manner that is completely undetectable to the user.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] The TrueCrypt disk encryption utility, as well as its derivative VeraCrypt, do not support TPM.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] The original TrueCrypt developers were of the opinion that the exclusive purpose of the TPM is "to protect against attacks that require the attacker to have administrator privileges, or physical access to the computer".
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] The attacker who has physical or administrative access to a computer can circumvent TPM, e.g., by installing a hardware keystroke logger, by resetting TPM, or by capturing memory contents and retrieving TPM-issued keys.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] The condemning text goes so far as to claim that TPM is entirely redundant.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] The VeraCrypt publisher has reproduced the original allegation with no changes other than replacing "TrueCrypt" with "VeraCrypt".
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] The author is right that, after achieving either unrestricted physical access or administrative privileges, it is only a matter of time before other security measures in place are bypassed.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] However, stopping an attacker in possession of administrative privileges has never been one of the goals of TPM (see § Uses for details), and TPM can stop some physical tampering.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] In 2015, Richard Stallman suggested replacing the term "trusted computing" with the term "treacherous computing" due to the danger that the computer can be made to systematically disobey its owner if the cryptographical keys are kept secret from them.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] In August 2023, Linus Torvalds, who was frustrated with AMD fTPM's stuttering bugs, opined, "Let's just disable the stupid fTPM `hwrnd` thing." He said the CPU-based random number generation, `rdrand`, was equally suitable, despite having its share of bugs.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] In 2010, Christopher Tarnovsky presented an attack against TPMs at Black Hat Briefings, where he claimed to be able to extract secrets from a single TPM.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] He was able to do this after 6 months of work by inserting a probe and spying on an internal bus for the Infineon SLE 66 CL PC.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] In case of physical access, computers with TPM 1.2 are vulnerable to cold boot attacks as long as the system is on or can be booted without a passphrase from shutdown, sleep or hibernation, which is the default setup for Windows computers with BitLocker full disk encryption.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] A fix was proposed, which has been adopted in the specifications for TPM 2.0.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] In 2009, the concept of shared authorisation data in TPM 1.2 was found to be flawed.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] An adversary given access to the data could spoof responses from the TPM.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] In 2015, as part of the Snowden revelations, it was revealed that in 2010 a US CIA team claimed at an internal conference to have carried out a differential power analysis attack against TPMs that was able to extract secrets.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] Main Trusted Boot (tboot) distributions before November 2017 are affected by a dynamic root of trust for measurement (DRTM) attack CVE-2017-16837, which affects computers running on Intel's Trusted eXecution Technology (TXT) for the boot-up routine.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] In October 2017, it was reported that a code library developed by Infineon, which had been in widespread use in its TPMs, contained a vulnerability, known as ROCA, which generated weak RSA key pairs that allowed private keys to be inferred from public keys.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] As a result, all systems depending upon the privacy of such weak keys are vulnerable to compromise, such as identity theft or spoofing.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] Cryptosystems that store encryption keys directly in the TPM without blinding could be at particular risk to these types of attacks, as passwords and other factors would be meaningless if the attacks can extract encryption secrets.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] Infineon has released firmware updates for its TPMs to manufacturers who have used them.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] In 2018, a design flaw in the TPM 2.0 specification for the static root of trust for measurement (SRTM) was reported (CVE-2018-6622).
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] It allows an adversary to reset and forge platform configuration registers which are designed to securely hold measurements of software that are used for bootstrapping a computer.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] Fixing it requires hardware-specific firmware patches.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] An attacker abuses power interrupts and TPM state restores to trick TPM into thinking that it is running on non-tampered components.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] In 2021, the Dolos Group showed an attack on a discrete TPM, where the TPM chip itself had some tamper resistance, but the other endpoints of its communication bus did not.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] They read a full-disk-encryption key as it was transmitted across the motherboard, and used it to decrypt the laptop's SSD.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] As of 2025, a TPM is provided by nearly all PC and notebook manufacturers in their products.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] There are also hybrid types; for example, TPM can be integrated into an Ethernet controller, thus eliminating the need for a separate motherboard component.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] Field upgrade is the TCG term for updating the TPM firmware.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] The update can be between TPM 1.2 and TPM 2.0, or between firmware versions.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] Some vendors limit the number of transitions between 1.2 and 2.0, and some restrict rollback to previous versions.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] Platform OEMs such as HP supply an upgrade tool.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] Since July 28, 2016, all new Microsoft device models, lines, or series (or updating the hardware configuration of an existing model, line, or series with a major update, such as CPU, graphic cards) implement, and enable by default TPM 2.0.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] TPM endorsement keys (EKs) are asymmetric key pairs unique to each TPM.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] The TPM manufacturer usually provisions endorsement key certificates in TPM non-volatile memory.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] The certificates assert that the TPM is authentic.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] Starting with TPM 2.0, the certificates are in X.509 DER format.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] After the TPM was manufactured, the EKs cannot be changed.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] For fTPM, the EKs are stored on CPU / chipset when it was manufactured.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] These manufacturers typically provide their certificate authority root (and sometimes intermediate) certificates on their web sites.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] To utilize a TPM, the user needs a software library that communicates with the TPM and provides a friendlier API than the raw TPM communication.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] Currently, there are several such open-source TPM 2.0 libraries.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] Some of them also support TPM 1.2, but mostly TPM 1.2 chips are now deprecated and modern development is focused on TPM 2.0.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] Typically, a TPM library provides an API with one-to-one mappings to TPM commands.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] The TCG specification calls this layer the System API (SAPI).
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] This way, the user has more control over the TPM operations, but the complexity is high.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] To hide some of the complexity, most libraries also offer simpler ways to invoke complex TPM operations.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] The TCG specification call these two layers Enhanced System API (ESAPI) and Feature API (FAPI).
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] There is currently only one stack that follows the TCG specification.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] All the other available open-source TPM libraries use their own form of richer API.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] There is an application note about an example project for the AURIX 32-bit SoC using the tpm2-tss library.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] Requires additional libraries (dotnet) to run on Linux.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] These TPM libraries are sometimes also called TPM stacks, because they provide the interface for the developer or user to interact with the TPM.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] As seen from the table, the TPM stacks abstract the operating system and transport layer, so the user could migrate one application between platforms.
[src:integrity-measurement/trusted-platform-module] For example, by using TPM stack API the user would interact the same way with a TPM, regardless if the physical chip is connected over SPI, I2C or LPC interface to the Host system.
